analogies in high-priest regalia as well as in various ways of claiming ownership in the Ancient Near East, such as inscribed monuments, the use of seals, and the branding of slaves. The NC presupposes that Yhwh has claimed Israel by placing Yhwh’s own name on her. In this light, the first two commands of the Decalogue reinforce the two sides of the covenant declaration: “I will be your God; you will be my people.” The first expresses the demand for exclusive worship and the second calls for proper representation. As a consequence, the NC invites a richer exploration of what it means to be a people in covenant with Yhwh—a people bearing his name among the nations. It also points to what is at stake when Israel carries that name “in vain.” The image of bearing Yhwh’s name offers a rich source for theological and ethical reflection that cannot be conveyed nonmetaphorically without distortion or loss of meaning.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 7aRELIGION / Biblical Criticism & Interpretation / Old Testament.2bisacsh  aAaronic Blessing.  aConceptual Metaphor Theory.  aDecalogue.  aDivine Name.  aExodus 20:7.  aExodus 28:29.  aHigh Priest.  aName Command.  aNumbers 6:27.  aTen Commandments.1 aBlock, Daniel I., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aImes, Carmen Joy, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPenn State University Press Complete eBook-Package 2018z978311074522140uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9781646022670?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781646022670423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781646022670/original  a978-3-11-074522-1  Penn State University Press Complete eBook-Package 2018b2018  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_PLTLJSIS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA